## 3. The Lexer

The lexer (or tokenizer) converts source text into a sequence of tokens. For Pebble, this is simple because each line is one instruction.

### What is a Token?

A token is a meaningful unit of source code. In the line:

```
add x 10 result
```

The tokens are: `add`, `x`, `10`, `result`.

We also need to track token *types*: is `10` a number or an identifier? Is `"hello"` a string literal?

Create `src/lexer.zig`:

```zig
// =============================================================================
// lexer.zig - Tokenizer for Pebble
// =============================================================================
//
// The lexer's job is to convert raw source text into tokens. This is the
// first stage of any language implementation.
//
// For Pebble, lexing is simple:
//   - Each line is one instruction
//   - Tokens are whitespace-separated
//   - Strings are "quoted like this"
//   - Comments start with # and extend to end of line
//
// We DON'T build a list of all tokens upfront. Instead, we provide an
// iterator that yields tokens one at a time. This is memory-efficient
// and idiomatic in Zig.
// =============================================================================

const std = @import("std");

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Token Types
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// Each token has a "type" that tells the parser what it represents.
// This is simpler than tracking every keyword — the parser will check
// if an identifier matches a keyword when needed.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const TokenType = enum {
    identifier,   // Keywords and variable names: add, x, myVar, label
    integer,      // Numeric literals: 42, -7, 0
    string,       // String literals: "hello world"
    newline,      // End of a line (important for our line-based syntax)
    eof,          // End of input
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Token Structure
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// A token bundles:
//   - Its type (what kind of token)
//   - Its text (the actual characters from source)
//   - Its location (for error messages)
//
// Note: `text` is a slice into the original source. We don't copy strings
// during lexing — this is efficient but means the source must outlive tokens.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const Token = struct {
    type: TokenType,
    text: []const u8,
    line: usize,  // 1-indexed line number for error messages
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// The Lexer
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// The lexer holds the source text and current position. It provides a
// `next()` function that returns the next token.
//
// Design choice: We use an iterator pattern rather than building a list.
// This is common in Zig — it's lazy and memory-efficient.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const Lexer = struct {
    source: []const u8,  // The complete source text
    pos: usize,          // Current byte position in source
    line: usize,         // Current line number (1-indexed)

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Constructor
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Zig doesn't have constructors, but the convention is an `init` function
    // that returns an instance of the struct.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    pub fn init(source: []const u8) Lexer {
        return Lexer{
            .source = source,
            .pos = 0,
            .line = 1,
        };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Get Next Token
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // This is the core lexer function. It:
    //   1. Skips whitespace (but not newlines — those are tokens!)
    //   2. Handles comments
    //   3. Recognizes strings, numbers, and identifiers
    //   4. Advances position past the token
    //
    // Returns: The next token, or an error if we hit invalid syntax
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    pub fn next(self: *Lexer) !Token {
        // Skip spaces and tabs (but NOT newlines)
        self.skipWhitespace();

        // Check for end of input
        if (self.isAtEnd()) {
            return Token{ .type = .eof, .text = "", .line = self.line };
        }

        // Check for comment — skip to end of line
        if (self.peek() == '#') {
            self.skipComment();
            // After skipping comment, we might be at newline or EOF
            // Recurse to get the actual next token
            return self.next();
        }

        // Check for newline
        if (self.peek() == '\n') {
            const token = Token{ .type = .newline, .text = "\n", .line = self.line };
            self.advance();
            self.line += 1;
            return token;
        }

        // Check for string literal
        if (self.peek() == '"') {
            return self.readString();
        }

        // Check for number (including negative numbers)
        if (isDigit(self.peek()) or
            (self.peek() == '-' and self.pos + 1 < self.source.len and isDigit(self.source[self.pos + 1])))
        {
            return self.readNumber();
        }

        // Otherwise, it's an identifier (keywords are identifiers for now)
        if (isIdentifierStart(self.peek())) {
            return self.readIdentifier();
        }

        // Unknown character — this is an error
        std.debug.print("Unexpected character '{}' at line {}\n", .{ self.peek(), self.line });
        return error.UnexpectedCharacter;
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Helper: Skip Whitespace (not newlines)
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn skipWhitespace(self: *Lexer) void {
        while (!self.isAtEnd() and (self.peek() == ' ' or self.peek() == '\t' or self.peek() == '\r')) {
            self.advance();
        }
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Helper: Skip Comment
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Comments start with # and extend to the end of the line.
    // We skip everything until (but not including) the newline.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn skipComment(self: *Lexer) void {
        while (!self.isAtEnd() and self.peek() != '\n') {
            self.advance();
        }
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Helper: Read String Literal
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Strings are enclosed in double quotes: "like this"
    // We don't handle escape sequences for simplicity.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn readString(self: *Lexer) !Token {
        const start_line = self.line;

        // Skip opening quote
        self.advance();
        const start = self.pos;

        // Read until closing quote
        while (!self.isAtEnd() and self.peek() != '"') {
            if (self.peek() == '\n') {
                return error.UnterminatedString;
            }
            self.advance();
        }

        if (self.isAtEnd()) {
            return error.UnterminatedString;
        }

        const text = self.source[start..self.pos];

        // Skip closing quote
        self.advance();

        return Token{ .type = .string, .text = text, .line = start_line };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Helper: Read Number Literal
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Numbers are sequences of digits, optionally prefixed with a minus sign.
    // We store the text; parsing to i64 happens later.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn readNumber(self: *Lexer) Token {
        const start = self.pos;
        const start_line = self.line;

        // Handle optional minus sign
        if (self.peek() == '-') {
            self.advance();
        }

        // Read digits
        while (!self.isAtEnd() and isDigit(self.peek())) {
            self.advance();
        }

        return Token{ .type = .integer, .text = self.source[start..self.pos], .line = start_line };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Helper: Read Identifier
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Identifiers start with a letter or underscore, then contain letters,
    // digits, or underscores.
    //
    // Keywords (like `add`, `jump`, `label`) are lexed as identifiers.
    // The parser will check if an identifier is a keyword.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn readIdentifier(self: *Lexer) Token {
        const start = self.pos;
        const start_line = self.line;

        while (!self.isAtEnd() and isIdentifierChar(self.peek())) {
            self.advance();
        }

        return Token{ .type = .identifier, .text = self.source[start..self.pos], .line = start_line };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Low-Level Helpers
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn peek(self: *Lexer) u8 {
        return self.source[self.pos];
    }

    fn advance(self: *Lexer) void {
        self.pos += 1;
    }

    fn isAtEnd(self: *Lexer) bool {
        return self.pos >= self.source.len;
    }
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Character Classification Functions
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// These are module-level functions (not methods) since they don't need state.
// In Zig, this is idiomatic — not everything needs to be a method.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

fn isDigit(c: u8) bool {
    return c >= '0' and c <= '9';
}

fn isIdentifierStart(c: u8) bool {
    return (c >= 'a' and c <= 'z') or
        (c >= 'A' and c <= 'Z') or
        c == '_';
}

fn isIdentifierChar(c: u8) bool {
    return isIdentifierStart(c) or isDigit(c);
}
```

**Zig Concepts Introduced:**

- `*Lexer` vs `Lexer` — The asterisk means "pointer to". Methods that modify the lexer take `self: *Lexer`. Methods that only read take `self: Lexer` (a copy, but since `Lexer` contains only a slice and two integers, copying is cheap). We use pointer here because we modify `pos` and `line`.

- `error.UnexpectedCharacter` — Error values. In Zig, errors are their own type. You can define error sets, but it's common to just use inferred error sets with `!ReturnType`.

- Module-level functions — `isDigit` isn't a method on any struct. It's just a function in the module. This is normal in Zig.

### Testing the Lexer

Update `main.zig`:

```zig
const std = @import("std");
const Lexer = @import("lexer.zig").Lexer;

pub fn main() !void {
    const stdout = std.io.getStdOut().writer();

    const source =
        \\set x 10
        \\add x 5 x  # add 5 to x
        \\print x
    ;

    var lexer = Lexer.init(source);

    while (true) {
        const token = try lexer.next();
        try stdout.print("Line {}: {s} \"{s}\"\n", .{
            token.line,
            @tagName(token.type),
            token.text,
        });
        if (token.type == .eof) break;
    }
}
```

**Zig Concept:**

- `\\` strings — Multi-line string literals. Each `\\` starts a new line, and the string doesn't include the actual newlines in your source code between lines. But it DOES include newlines where the lines end.

Wait, that's confusing. Let me clarify: `\\` strings are "raw" and each line starts with `\\`. The result includes newlines *within* the string content. So the source above is equivalent to `"set x 10\nadd x 5 x  # add 5 to x\nprint x"`.

