## 4. The Parser

The parser transforms tokens into structured instructions. For Pebble, this is straightforward — we're building a list of instructions, not a tree.

### What is an Instruction?

Each line becomes one `Instruction`:

```
set x 10        →  Instruction{ .opcode = .set, .operands = ["x", "10"] }
add a b c       →  Instruction{ .opcode = .add, .operands = ["a", "b", "c"] }
label loop      →  Instruction{ .opcode = .label, .operands = ["loop"] }
```

### The Label Problem

Control flow (`jump`, `jumpif`, `call`) references labels by name. But when we encounter `jump loop`, we might not have seen `label loop` yet!

**Solution:** Two-pass parsing.
1. **First pass:** Parse all instructions, record label positions
2. **Second pass:** Resolve label names to instruction indices

For simplicity, we'll do this in one pass by storing labels in a hash map, then resolving jumps after parsing.

Create `src/parser.zig`:

```zig
// =============================================================================
// parser.zig - Parser for Pebble
// =============================================================================
//
// The parser converts tokens into a list of instructions. This is simple
// because Pebble has no nesting — each line is one instruction.
//
// The tricky part is labels. When we see `jump foo`, we need to know where
// `foo` is. We solve this by:
//   1. Parsing all instructions, storing labels in a map
//   2. After parsing, resolving label names to instruction indices
//
// This means jump targets are stored as indices, not names, in the final
// instruction list. This makes the interpreter faster and simpler.
// =============================================================================

const std = @import("std");
const Lexer = @import("lexer.zig").Lexer;
const Token = @import("lexer.zig").Token;
const TokenType = @import("lexer.zig").TokenType;

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Opcodes
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// Every instruction has an opcode that identifies what it does.
// Using an enum gives us type safety and exhaustiveness checking in switches.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const Opcode = enum {
    // Variables
    set,    // set <var> <value>
    copy,   // copy <src> <dest>

    // Arithmetic
    add,    // add <a> <b> <dest>
    sub,    // sub <a> <b> <dest>
    mul,    // mul <a> <b> <dest>
    div,    // div <a> <b> <dest>
    mod,    // mod <a> <b> <dest>

    // Comparison (sets flag)
    eq,     // eq <a> <b>
    neq,    // neq <a> <b>
    lt,     // lt <a> <b>
    gt,     // gt <a> <b>

    // String operations
    concat, // concat <a> <b> <dest>
    len,    // len <source> <dest>

    // Array operations
    array,  // array <name> <size>
    geta,   // geta <arr> <index> <dest>
    seta,   // seta <arr> <index> <value>

    // I/O
    print,  // print <value>
    read,   // read <prompt> <dest>

    // Control flow
    label,  // label <name>       (pseudo-instruction, removed after parsing)
    jump,   // jump <label>
    jumpif, // jumpif <label>
    jumpnot,// jumpnot <label>
    call,   // call <label>
    ret,    // ret

    // Misc
    halt,   // halt
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Operand
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// An operand is either:
//   - An identifier (variable name or label name)
//   - An integer literal
//   - A string literal
//
// We use a tagged union again. Notice how this pattern recurs!
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const Operand = union(enum) {
    identifier: []const u8,
    integer: i64,
    string: []const u8,

    // For debugging
    pub fn format(
        self: Operand,
        comptime fmt: []const u8,
        options: std.fmt.FormatOptions,
        writer: anytype,
    ) !void {
        _ = fmt;
        _ = options;
        switch (self) {
            .identifier => |s| try writer.print("id:{s}", .{s}),
            .integer => |n| try writer.print("int:{d}", .{n}),
            .string => |s| try writer.print("str:\"{s}\"", .{s}),
        }
    }
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Instruction
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// A parsed instruction with opcode and operands.
// We store up to 3 operands (the max any instruction needs).
//
// Using an array instead of individual fields keeps things uniform.
// The `operand_count` tells us how many are valid.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const Instruction = struct {
    opcode: Opcode,
    operands: [3]Operand,
    operand_count: u8,
    line: usize,  // Source line for error messages

    // Helper to get an operand safely
    pub fn getOperand(self: Instruction, index: usize) ?Operand {
        if (index >= self.operand_count) return null;
        return self.operands[index];
    }
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Parser
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const Parser = struct {
    lexer: Lexer,
    current: Token,
    allocator: std.mem.Allocator,

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Constructor
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    pub fn init(source: []const u8, allocator: std.mem.Allocator) !Parser {
        var lexer = Lexer.init(source);
        const first_token = try lexer.next();

        return Parser{
            .lexer = lexer,
            .current = first_token,
            .allocator = allocator,
        };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Main Parse Function
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Returns a list of instructions and a map of label names to indices.
    // The caller can use the label map to resolve jump targets.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    pub fn parse(self: *Parser) !ParseResult {
        var instructions = std.ArrayList(Instruction).init(self.allocator);
        var labels = std.StringHashMap(usize).init(self.allocator);

        while (self.current.type != .eof) {
            // Skip blank lines
            if (self.current.type == .newline) {
                _ = try self.advance();
                continue;
            }

            const inst = try self.parseInstruction();

            // If it's a label, record its position but don't add to instruction list
            if (inst.opcode == .label) {
                const label_name = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                try labels.put(label_name, instructions.items.len);
            } else {
                try instructions.append(inst);
            }
        }

        return ParseResult{
            .instructions = instructions,
            .labels = labels,
        };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Parse Single Instruction
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn parseInstruction(self: *Parser) !Instruction {
        // First token should be the opcode (an identifier)
        if (self.current.type != .identifier) {
            std.debug.print("Expected instruction at line {}, got {s}\n", .{
                self.current.line,
                @tagName(self.current.type),
            });
            return error.ExpectedInstruction;
        }

        const opcode_str = self.current.text;
        const line = self.current.line;
        _ = try self.advance();

        // Convert string to opcode
        const opcode = stringToOpcode(opcode_str) orelse {
            std.debug.print("Unknown instruction '{s}' at line {}\n", .{ opcode_str, line });
            return error.UnknownInstruction;
        };

        // Parse operands based on opcode
        const expected_operands = opcodeOperandCount(opcode);
        var operands: [3]Operand = undefined;
        var count: u8 = 0;

        while (count < expected_operands) {
            if (self.current.type == .newline or self.current.type == .eof) {
                std.debug.print("Expected operand at line {}\n", .{line});
                return error.MissingOperand;
            }

            operands[count] = try self.parseOperand();
            count += 1;
        }

        // Expect newline or EOF after instruction
        if (self.current.type != .newline and self.current.type != .eof) {
            std.debug.print("Expected end of line at line {}\n", .{line});
            return error.ExpectedEndOfLine;
        }

        // Consume the newline
        if (self.current.type == .newline) {
            _ = try self.advance();
        }

        return Instruction{
            .opcode = opcode,
            .operands = operands,
            .operand_count = count,
            .line = line,
        };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Parse Single Operand
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn parseOperand(self: *Parser) !Operand {
        const token = self.current;
        _ = try self.advance();

        return switch (token.type) {
            .identifier => Operand{ .identifier = token.text },
            .integer => Operand{
                .integer = std.fmt.parseInt(i64, token.text, 10) catch {
                    std.debug.print("Invalid integer '{s}' at line {}\n", .{ token.text, token.line });
                    return error.InvalidInteger;
                },
            },
            .string => Operand{ .string = token.text },
            else => {
                std.debug.print("Unexpected token type for operand at line {}\n", .{token.line});
                return error.UnexpectedToken;
            },
        };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Token Advancement
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn advance(self: *Parser) !Token {
        const prev = self.current;
        self.current = try self.lexer.next();
        return prev;
    }
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Parse Result
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// The parser returns both the instructions and the label map.
// This bundles them together for convenience.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const ParseResult = struct {
    instructions: std.ArrayList(Instruction),
    labels: std.StringHashMap(usize),
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Helper Functions
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

fn stringToOpcode(s: []const u8) ?Opcode {
    const map = std.StaticStringMap(Opcode).initComptime(.{
        .{ "set", .set },
        .{ "copy", .copy },
        .{ "add", .add },
        .{ "sub", .sub },
        .{ "mul", .mul },
        .{ "div", .div },
        .{ "mod", .mod },
        .{ "eq", .eq },
        .{ "neq", .neq },
        .{ "lt", .lt },
        .{ "gt", .gt },
        .{ "concat", .concat },
        .{ "len", .len },
        .{ "array", .array },
        .{ "geta", .geta },
        .{ "seta", .seta },
        .{ "print", .print },
        .{ "read", .read },
        .{ "label", .label },
        .{ "jump", .jump },
        .{ "jumpif", .jumpif },
        .{ "jumpnot", .jumpnot },
        .{ "call", .call },
        .{ "ret", .ret },
        .{ "halt", .halt },
    });

    return map.get(s);
}

fn opcodeOperandCount(op: Opcode) u8 {
    return switch (op) {
        .ret, .halt => 0,
        .label, .jump, .jumpif, .jumpnot, .call, .print => 1,
        .set, .copy, .eq, .neq, .lt, .gt, .len, .array, .read => 2,
        .add, .sub, .mul, .div, .mod, .concat, .geta, .seta => 3,
    };
}
```

**Zig Concepts Introduced:**

- `std.ArrayList` — A dynamic array. Similar to `Vec<T>` in Rust or `std::vector<T>` in C++.

- `std.StringHashMap` — A hash map with string keys. Zig's standard library has several map types for different needs.

- `std.StaticStringMap` — A compile-time hash map. `initComptime` builds the map at compile time, so lookups are fast at runtime.

- `std.mem.Allocator` — Zig has no hidden allocations. You explicitly pass allocators where memory is needed. This is verbose but gives you complete control.

- `undefined` — Uninitialized memory. We use this for the `operands` array since we'll fill it in immediately. Using `undefined` is dangerous if you forget to initialize!

