## 5. The Interpreter

Now the fun part! The interpreter executes our parsed instructions.

### The Execution Model

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│               Interpreter                    │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  instructions: [Instruction]   (code)       │
│  pc: usize                     (current)    │
│  variables: HashMap(str→Value) (storage)    │
│  call_stack: [usize]           (returns)    │
│  flag: bool                    (comparison) │
│  running: bool                 (halt?)      │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

The main loop:
```
while running:
    instruction = instructions[pc]
    execute(instruction)
    pc += 1  (unless jump)
```

Create `src/interpreter.zig`:

```zig
// =============================================================================
// interpreter.zig - Pebble Interpreter
// =============================================================================
//
// The interpreter executes parsed instructions. It maintains:
//   - A program counter (pc) pointing to the current instruction
//   - A hash map of variables
//   - A call stack for subroutine returns
//   - A flag for conditional jumps
//
// The main loop fetches an instruction, executes it, and advances pc.
// Jump instructions modify pc directly instead of incrementing.
// =============================================================================

const std = @import("std");
const Value = @import("value.zig").Value;
const Instruction = @import("parser.zig").Instruction;
const Opcode = @import("parser.zig").Opcode;
const Operand = @import("parser.zig").Operand;

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Runtime Errors
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// We define specific error types for different runtime failures.
// This helps with debugging and could enable better error messages.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const RuntimeError = error{
    UndefinedVariable,
    TypeMismatch,
    DivisionByZero,
    InvalidArrayIndex,
    StackUnderflow,
    UnresolvedLabel,
    OutOfMemory,
    InvalidInput,
};

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Interpreter
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub const Interpreter = struct {
    // The program
    instructions: []const Instruction,
    labels: std.StringHashMap(usize),

    // Execution state
    pc: usize,                              // Program counter
    variables: std.StringHashMap(Value),    // Variable storage
    call_stack: std.ArrayList(usize),       // Return addresses
    flag: bool,                             // Last comparison result
    running: bool,                          // Continue executing?

    // Resources
    allocator: std.mem.Allocator,
    stdout: std.fs.File.Writer,
    stdin: std.fs.File.Reader,

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Constructor
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    pub fn init(
        instructions: []const Instruction,
        labels: std.StringHashMap(usize),
        allocator: std.mem.Allocator,
    ) Interpreter {
        return Interpreter{
            .instructions = instructions,
            .labels = labels,
            .pc = 0,
            .variables = std.StringHashMap(Value).init(allocator),
            .call_stack = std.ArrayList(usize).init(allocator),
            .flag = false,
            .running = true,
            .allocator = allocator,
            .stdout = std.io.getStdOut().writer(),
            .stdin = std.io.getStdIn().reader(),
        };
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Cleanup
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    pub fn deinit(self: *Interpreter) void {
        // Free any arrays stored in variables
        var it = self.variables.valueIterator();
        while (it.next()) |value| {
            if (value.* == .array) {
                value.array.deinit();
            }
        }
        self.variables.deinit();
        self.call_stack.deinit();
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Run the Program
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // This is the main loop. It continues until:
    //   - A `halt` instruction sets running = false
    //   - We run past the end of instructions
    //   - An error occurs
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    pub fn run(self: *Interpreter) !void {
        while (self.running and self.pc < self.instructions.len) {
            const inst = self.instructions[self.pc];
            try self.execute(inst);
        }
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Execute Single Instruction
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // This is a big switch on the opcode. Each case handles one instruction.
    // Some instructions advance pc automatically, others (jumps) set it.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn execute(self: *Interpreter, inst: Instruction) !void {
        switch (inst.opcode) {
            // -----------------------------------------------------------------
            // Variables
            // -----------------------------------------------------------------

            .set => {
                // set <var> <value>
                const var_name = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                const value = try self.resolveOperand(inst.operands[1]);
                try self.variables.put(var_name, value);
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            .copy => {
                // copy <src> <dest>
                const src_name = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                const dest_name = inst.operands[1].identifier;
                const value = self.variables.get(src_name) orelse
                    return RuntimeError.UndefinedVariable;
                try self.variables.put(dest_name, value);
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            // -----------------------------------------------------------------
            // Arithmetic
            // -----------------------------------------------------------------

            .add, .sub, .mul, .div, .mod => {
                const a = try self.resolveToInteger(inst.operands[0]);
                const b = try self.resolveToInteger(inst.operands[1]);
                const dest = inst.operands[2].identifier;

                const result: i64 = switch (inst.opcode) {
                    .add => a + b,
                    .sub => a - b,
                    .mul => a * b,
                    .div => if (b == 0) return RuntimeError.DivisionByZero else @divTrunc(a, b),
                    .mod => if (b == 0) return RuntimeError.DivisionByZero else @mod(a, b),
                    else => unreachable,
                };

                try self.variables.put(dest, Value{ .integer = result });
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            // -----------------------------------------------------------------
            // Comparisons
            // -----------------------------------------------------------------

            .eq, .neq, .lt, .gt => {
                const a = try self.resolveOperand(inst.operands[0]);
                const b = try self.resolveOperand(inst.operands[1]);

                // For simplicity, only compare integers
                const a_int = a.asInteger() orelse return RuntimeError.TypeMismatch;
                const b_int = b.asInteger() orelse return RuntimeError.TypeMismatch;

                self.flag = switch (inst.opcode) {
                    .eq => a_int == b_int,
                    .neq => a_int != b_int,
                    .lt => a_int < b_int,
                    .gt => a_int > b_int,
                    else => unreachable,
                };
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            // -----------------------------------------------------------------
            // Strings
            // -----------------------------------------------------------------

            .concat => {
                const a = try self.resolveToString(inst.operands[0]);
                const b = try self.resolveToString(inst.operands[1]);
                const dest = inst.operands[2].identifier;

                // Allocate new string for result
                const result = try std.fmt.allocPrint(self.allocator, "{s}{s}", .{ a, b });
                try self.variables.put(dest, Value{ .string = result });
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            .len => {
                const source = try self.resolveOperand(inst.operands[0]);
                const dest = inst.operands[1].identifier;

                const length: i64 = switch (source) {
                    .string => |s| @intCast(s.len),
                    .array => |arr| @intCast(arr.items.len),
                    else => return RuntimeError.TypeMismatch,
                };

                try self.variables.put(dest, Value{ .integer = length });
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            // -----------------------------------------------------------------
            // Arrays
            // -----------------------------------------------------------------

            .array => {
                const name = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                const size = try self.resolveToInteger(inst.operands[1]);

                var arr = std.ArrayList(Value).init(self.allocator);
                // Pre-fill with zeros
                try arr.appendNTimes(Value{ .integer = 0 }, @intCast(size));

                try self.variables.put(name, Value{ .array = arr });
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            .seta => {
                // seta <arr> <index> <value>
                const arr_name = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                const index = try self.resolveToInteger(inst.operands[1]);
                const value = try self.resolveOperand(inst.operands[2]);

                const entry = self.variables.getPtr(arr_name) orelse
                    return RuntimeError.UndefinedVariable;

                if (entry.* != .array) return RuntimeError.TypeMismatch;

                const idx: usize = @intCast(index);
                if (idx >= entry.array.items.len) return RuntimeError.InvalidArrayIndex;

                entry.array.items[idx] = value;
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            .geta => {
                // geta <arr> <index> <dest>
                const arr_name = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                const index = try self.resolveToInteger(inst.operands[1]);
                const dest = inst.operands[2].identifier;

                const arr_val = self.variables.get(arr_name) orelse
                    return RuntimeError.UndefinedVariable;

                if (arr_val != .array) return RuntimeError.TypeMismatch;

                const idx: usize = @intCast(index);
                if (idx >= arr_val.array.items.len) return RuntimeError.InvalidArrayIndex;

                const value = arr_val.array.items[idx];
                try self.variables.put(dest, value);
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            // -----------------------------------------------------------------
            // I/O
            // -----------------------------------------------------------------

            .print => {
                const value = try self.resolveOperand(inst.operands[0]);
                try self.stdout.print("{}\n", .{value});
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            .read => {
                // read <prompt> <dest>
                const prompt = switch (inst.operands[0]) {
                    .string => |s| s,
                    else => return RuntimeError.TypeMismatch,
                };
                const dest = inst.operands[1].identifier;

                // Display prompt
                try self.stdout.print("{s}", .{prompt});

                // Read line
                var buf: [256]u8 = undefined;
                const line = self.stdin.readUntilDelimiter(&buf, '\n') catch |err| {
                    if (err == error.EndOfStream) {
                        return RuntimeError.InvalidInput;
                    }
                    return RuntimeError.InvalidInput;
                };

                // Try to parse as integer, otherwise store as string
                if (std.fmt.parseInt(i64, line, 10)) |num| {
                    try self.variables.put(dest, Value{ .integer = num });
                } else |_| {
                    // Store as string (we need to allocate since buf is temporary)
                    const str = try self.allocator.dupe(u8, line);
                    try self.variables.put(dest, Value{ .string = str });
                }

                self.pc += 1;
            },

            // -----------------------------------------------------------------
            // Control Flow
            // -----------------------------------------------------------------

            .label => {
                // Labels are handled during parsing; they shouldn't appear here
                self.pc += 1;
            },

            .jump => {
                const target = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                self.pc = self.labels.get(target) orelse
                    return RuntimeError.UnresolvedLabel;
            },

            .jumpif => {
                if (self.flag) {
                    const target = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                    self.pc = self.labels.get(target) orelse
                        return RuntimeError.UnresolvedLabel;
                } else {
                    self.pc += 1;
                }
            },

            .jumpnot => {
                if (!self.flag) {
                    const target = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                    self.pc = self.labels.get(target) orelse
                        return RuntimeError.UnresolvedLabel;
                } else {
                    self.pc += 1;
                }
            },

            .call => {
                const target = inst.operands[0].identifier;
                // Push return address
                try self.call_stack.append(self.pc + 1);
                // Jump to target
                self.pc = self.labels.get(target) orelse
                    return RuntimeError.UnresolvedLabel;
            },

            .ret => {
                if (self.call_stack.items.len == 0) {
                    return RuntimeError.StackUnderflow;
                }
                self.pc = self.call_stack.pop();
            },

            .halt => {
                self.running = false;
            },
        }
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Value Resolution Helpers
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // These convert operands to values. An operand might be:
    //   - A literal (integer or string) → use directly
    //   - An identifier → look up in variables
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    fn resolveOperand(self: *Interpreter, op: Operand) !Value {
        return switch (op) {
            .integer => |n| Value{ .integer = n },
            .string => |s| Value{ .string = s },
            .identifier => |name| self.variables.get(name) orelse
                RuntimeError.UndefinedVariable,
        };
    }

    fn resolveToInteger(self: *Interpreter, op: Operand) !i64 {
        const value = try self.resolveOperand(op);
        return value.asInteger() orelse RuntimeError.TypeMismatch;
    }

    fn resolveToString(self: *Interpreter, op: Operand) ![]const u8 {
        const value = try self.resolveOperand(op);
        return value.asString() orelse RuntimeError.TypeMismatch;
    }
};
```

**Zig Concepts Introduced:**

- `error{...}` — A custom error set. We list all possible runtime errors. This enables precise error handling.

- `@intCast` — Explicit integer conversion. Zig doesn't implicitly convert between integer types. You must be explicit, which prevents subtle bugs.

- `@divTrunc` — Integer division that truncates toward zero. Zig has multiple division functions (`@divFloor`, `@divExact`) for different rounding behaviors.

- `unreachable` — Tells the compiler "this case should never happen". If it does, it's a bug and the program crashes with a helpful message.

- `getPtr` vs `get` — `get` returns a copy of the value; `getPtr` returns a pointer to it. We need `getPtr` for arrays so we can modify them in place.

